hildren and women. Framed by War traces the arc of intimate relations that served as these foundations. To suture a fragmented past, Susie Woo looks to US and South Korean government documents and military correspondence; US aid organization records; Korean orphanage registers; US and South Korean newspapers and magazines; and photographs, interviews, films, and performances. Integrating history with visual and cultural analysis, Woo chronicles how Americans went from knowing very little about Koreans to making them family, and how Korean children and women who did not choose war found ways to navigate its aftermath in South Korea, the United States, and spaces in between.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aKorean War, 1950-1953xChildrenxSocial conditions. 0aKorean War, 1950-1953xWomenxSocial conditions. 0aKoreansxCultural assimilationzUnited States. 0aKoreanszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aOrphanszKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aWar brideszKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh  aAmerican-Korean Foundation.  aChild Placement Service.  aChristian Children’s Fund.  aCold War internationalism.  aCold War.  aHarry Holt.  aImmigration and Naturalization Service.  aInternational Social Service.  aJapanese military bride.  aKim Sisters.  aKorean Children’s Choir.  aKorean Orphan Choir.  aKorean War.  aKorean adoptees.  aKorean military bride.  aKorean military brides.  aKorean-black children.  aOrientalism.  aPearl Buck.  aPresident Rhee Syngman.  aUS imperialism.  aUS militarization.  aUS militarized prostitution.  aUS military-industrial complex.  aUS missionaries.  aUS racialization.  aUS-Korea relations.  aUnited Service Organizations.  aWorld Vision.  aadoption